ed each other. Klein maintains that the idea of a collision between people with and without history still dominates public memory. But the collision, he believes, resounds even more powerfully in the historical imagination, which creates conflicts between narration and knowledge and carries them into the language used to describe the American frontier. In Klein's words, "We remain obscurely entangled in philosophies of history we no longer profess, and the very idea of 'America' balances on history's shifting frontiers."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFrontier and pioneer lifexHistoriographyxUnited States. 0aFrontier and pioneer lifezUnited StatesxHistoriography. 0aFrontier thesis. 0aHistoriographyxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aHistoriographyxHistoryy20th centuryxUnited States. 0aHistoriographyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aIndians of North AmericaxFirst contact with EuropeansxHistoriography. 0aIndians of North AmericaxFirst contact with other peoplesxHistoriography. 0aIndians, Treatment ofxHistoriographyxNorth America. 0aIndians, Treatment ofzNorth AmericaxHistoriography. 4acivilization. 4ademocracy. 4ahistory of the Americas. 4ahistory. 4aimagination. 4aknowledge. 4amemory. 4anation. 4aphilosophy. 4apublic. 4asociology. 4aspace. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  aamerican democracy.  aamerican frontier.  aamerican history.  aamerican west.  aborderlands.  acolonialism.  acowboys and indians.  aenvironmental history.  afrontier.  ahistorical imagination.  ahistorical narrative.  ahistory.  aindigenous peoples and history.  aindigenous.  aliterary criticism.  anative america.  anative americans.  anatural history.  anew world.  anoble savage.  anonfiction.  aold world.  asettler co